Commands I learned:
1. mkdir -- makes folders/directories
2. touch -- creates new, empty files. if the file exists, it just updates the timestamp (viewable using ls -l)
3. rmdir -- removes directories. not files. cant delete directories with contents in them.
--> rmdir -p: deletes a folder AND all its parent folders. useful for deleting useless nested folders from the inside
4. rm -- removes files.
--> rm -r: removes directories and files and anything inside them. 
--> rm -v: gives the files deleted verbally/written.
--> rm -i: asks permission before every decision.
5. open -- opens files or directories in GUI
6. mv -- moves files into a specified directory. or, renames file. "mv -filename- -directory/rename-"
7. cp -- copies files into a specified directory
8. head -- spews out first ten lines of a file. 
--> head -n takes in number of lines then file name to spew out
9. tail -- like heads, but starts at the end of the file
--> tail -f appends the lines spewed out as the file grows. if new content is added, it updates in real time
10. date -- slef explanatory
11. redirecting files using > or >>. makes file if the file name doesnt exist. can also add content to empty files.
12. cat -- concatenates the contents of two files
13. less -- spews out contents of a file in a separate page
14. echo -- echo
15. wc -- prints line, word count, and bytes of anything
16. piping -- |
--> used to chain commands together. i.e., cat -file1- -file2- | wc
or, i.e., cat -file1- -file2- >> -file3- | cp  -file-name /home/user/Desktop | wc /home/user/Desktop/-file3-
